{"title_page": "Wikispecies", "text_new": "{{selfref|For project information on how Wikispecies relates to English Wikipedia, see [[Wikipedia:Wikispecies]].}}\n{{selfref|To go directly to the Wikispecies project, see [https://species.wikimedia.org/wiki/Main_Page www.Wikispecies.com].}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name             = Wikispecies\n| favicon          =\n| logo             = [[Image:WikiSpecies.svg|100px|The current Wikispecies logo]]\n| screenshot       = [[File:Wikispecies screenshot.png|250px|Detail of the Wikispecies main page.]]\n| caption          = Screenshot of species.wikimedia.org home page on 3 May 2011\n| url              = {{URL|https://species.wikimedia.org/}}\n| commercial       = No\n| type             = Species directory\n| registration     = Optional\n| owner            = [[Wikimedia Foundation]]\n| author           = [[:species:User:Benedikt|Benedikt Mandl]] (proposed project in 2004); [[Jimmy Wales]] and the Wikimedia community\n| launch_date      = {{Start date and years ago|mf=yes|2004|09|13}}\n| current_status   =\n| revenue          =\n| alexa            =\n}}\n\n'''Wikispecies''' is a [[wiki]]-based online project supported by the [[Wikimedia Foundation]]. Its aim is to create a comprehensive [[free content]] catalogue of all [[species]]; the project is directed at scientists, rather than at the general public. [[Jimmy Wales]] stated that editors are not required to [[fax]] in their degrees, but that submissions will have to pass muster with a technical audience.<ref>{{cite journal |year=2005 |title=Calling all taxonomists |journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]] |volume=307 |issue=5712 |pages=1021 |doi=10.1126/science.307.5712.1021a|doi-access=free }}</ref><ref name=AS>{{cite news |title=WikiSpecies |newspaper=[[American Scientist|American Scientist Online]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050430034914/http://www.americanscientist.org/template/SiteOfTheWeekTypeDetail/assetid/43122 |url=http://www.americanscientist.org/template/SiteOfTheWeekTypeDetail/assetid/43122 |archivedate=30 April 2005 |date=25 April 2005 |publisher=Sigma Xi |accessdate=3 February 2014}}</ref> Wikispecies is available under the [[GNU Free Documentation License]] and [[Creative Commons licenses|CC BY-SA 3.0]].\n\nStarted in September 2004, with [[biologist]]s across the world invited to contribute,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Peplow|first=Mark|date=15 March 2005|title=Species list reaches half-million mark|journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]|doi=10.1038/news050314-6}}</ref> the project had grown a framework encompassing the [[Linnaean taxonomy]] with links to [[Wikipedia]] articles on individual species by April 2005.<ref name=AS />\n\n== History ==\n[[:species:User:Benedikt|Benedikt Mandl]] co-ordinated the efforts of several people who are interested in getting involved with the project and contacted potential supporters in early summer 2004. Databases were evaluated and the administrators contacted, some of them have agreed on providing their data for Wikispecies. Mandl defined two major tasks:\n# Figure out how the contents of the data base would need to be presented\u2014by asking experts, potential non-professional users and comparing that with existing databases\n# Figure out how to do the software, which hardware is required and how to cover the costs\u2014by asking experts, looking for fellow volunteers and potential sponsors\n\nAdvantages and disadvantages were widely discussed by the wikimedia-I mailing list. The board of directors of the [[Wikimedia Foundation]] voted by 4 to 0 in favor of the establishment of a Wikispecies. The project was launched in August 2004 and is hosted at species.wikimedia.org. It was officially merged to a sister project of Wikimedia Foundation on September 14, 2004.fghhp46hnrkmg\njj\n* On October 10, 2006, the project exceeded 75,000 articles.\n* On May 20, 2007, the project exceeded 100,000 articles with a total of 5,495 registered users.\n* On September 8, 2008, the project exceeded 150,000 articles with a total of 9,224 registered users.\n* On October 23, 2011, the project reached 300,000 articles.\n* On June 16, 2014, the project reached 400,000 articles.\n* On January 7, 2017, the project reached 500,000 articles.\n* On October 30, 2018, the project reached 600,000 articles, and a total of 1.12 million pages.\n* On December 8, 2019, the project reached 700,000 articles, and a total of 1.33 million pages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://species.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:Statistics|title=Statistics|publisher=Wikispecies|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAs a database for taxonomy and nomenclature, Wikispecies comprises taxon pages, and additionally pages about synonyms, taxon authorities, taxonomical publications, and institutions or repositories holding type specimen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://species.wikimedia.org/wiki/Wikispecies:Page_types|title=Wikispecies:Page types|publisher=Wikispecies|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Policies ==\nWikispecies has disabled local upload and asks users to use images from [[commons:Main Page|Wikimedia Commons]]. Wikispecies does not allow the use of content that does not conform to a free license.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[All Species Foundation]]\n* [[Catalogue of Life]]\n* [[Encyclopedia of Life]]\n* [[Tree of Life Web Project]]\n* [[List of online encyclopedias]]\n* [[The Plant List]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[[species:Main_Page|Wikispecies, The free species directory that anyone can edit]]\n*[[species:Wikispecies:Community_Portal|Species Community Portal]]\n*[[species:Wikispecies:Charter|The Wikispecies Charter]], written by Wales.\n*{{Commons-inline}}\n\n{{Wikimedia Foundation}}\n\n[[Category:Biodiversity databases]]\n[[Category:Biology websites]]\n[[Category:Botanical nomenclature]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2004]]\n[[Category:Multilingual websites]]\n[[Category:Phylogenetics]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy (biology)]]\n[[Category:Wikimedia projects]]\n[[Category:Zoological nomenclature]]\n[[Category:Advertising-free websites]]\n", "text_old": "{{selfref|For project information on how Wikispecies relates to English Wikipedia, see [[Wikipedia:Wikispecies]].}}\n{{selfref|To go directly to the Wikispecies project, see [https://species.wikimedia.org/wiki/Main_Page www.Wikispecies.com].}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name             = Wikispecies\n| favicon          =\n| logo             = [[Image:WikiSpecies.svg|100px|The current Wikispecies logo]]\n| screenshot       = [[File:Wikispecies screenshot.png|250px|Detail of the Wikispecies main page.]]\n| caption          = Screenshot of species.wikimedia.org home page on 3 May 2011\n| url              = {{URL|https://species.wikimedia.org/}}\n| commercial       = No\n| type             = Species directory\n| registration     = Optional\n| owner            = [[Wikimedia Foundation]]\n| author           = [[:species:User:Benedikt|Benedikt Mandl]] (proposed project in 2004); [[Jimmy Wales]] and the Wikimedia community\n| launch_date      = {{Start date and years ago|mf=yes|2004|09|13}}\n| current_status   =\n| revenue          =\n| alexa            =\n}}\n\n'''Wikispecies''' is a [[wiki]]-based online project supported by the [[Wikimedia Foundation]]. Its aim is to create a comprehensive [[free content]] catalogue of all [[species]]; the project is directed at scientists, rather than at the general public. [[Jimmy Wales]] stated that editors are not required to [[fax]] in their degrees, but that submissions will have to pass muster with a technical audience.<ref>{{cite journal |year=2005 |title=Calling all taxonomists |journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]] |volume=307 |issue=5712 |pages=1021 |doi=10.1126/science.307.5712.1021a|doi-access=free }}</ref><ref name=AS>{{cite news |title=WikiSpecies |newspaper=[[American Scientist|American Scientist Online]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050430034914/http://www.americanscientist.org/template/SiteOfTheWeekTypeDetail/assetid/43122 |url=http://www.americanscientist.org/template/SiteOfTheWeekTypeDetail/assetid/43122 |archivedate=30 April 2005 |date=25 April 2005 |publisher=Sigma Xi |accessdate=3 February 2014}}</ref> Wikispecies is available under the [[GNU Free Documentation License]] and [[Creative Commons licenses|CC BY-SA 3.0]].\n\nStarted in September 2004, with [[biologist]]s across the world invited to contribute,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Peplow|first=Mark|date=15 March 2005|title=Species list reaches half-million mark|journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]|doi=10.1038/news050314-6}}</ref> the project had grown a framework encompassing the [[Linnaean taxonomy]] with links to [[Wikipedia]] articles on individual species by April 2005.<ref name=AS />\n\n== History ==\n[[:species:User:Benedikt|Benedikt Mandl]] co-ordinated the efforts of several people who are interested in getting involved with the project and contacted potential supporters in early summer 2004. Databases were evaluated and the administrators contacted, some of them have agreed on providing their data for Wikispecies. Mandl defined two major tasks:\n# Figure out how the contents of the data base would need to be presented\u2014by asking experts, potential non-professional users and comparing that with existing databases\n# Figure out how to do the software, which hardware is required and how to cover the costs\u2014by asking experts, looking for fellow volunteers and potential sponsors\n\nAdvantages and disadvantages were widely discussed by the wikimedia-I mailing list. The board of directors of the [[Wikimedia Foundation]] voted by 4 to 0 in favor of the establishment of a Wikispecies. The project was launched in August 2004 and is hosted at species.wikimedia.org. It was officially merged to a sister project of Wikimedia Foundation on September 14, 2004.\n* On October 10, 2006, the project exceeded 75,000 articles.\n* On May 20, 2007, the project exceeded 100,000 articles with a total of 5,495 registered users.\n* On September 8, 2008, the project exceeded 150,000 articles with a total of 9,224 registered users.\n* On October 23, 2011, the project reached 300,000 articles.\n* On June 16, 2014, the project reached 400,000 articles.\n* On January 7, 2017, the project reached 500,000 articles.\n* On October 30, 2018, the project reached 600,000 articles, and a total of 1.12 million pages.\n* On December 8, 2019, the project reached 700,000 articles, and a total of 1.33 million pages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://species.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:Statistics|title=Statistics|publisher=Wikispecies|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAs a database for taxonomy and nomenclature, Wikispecies comprises taxon pages, and additionally pages about synonyms, taxon authorities, taxonomical publications, and institutions or repositories holding type specimen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://species.wikimedia.org/wiki/Wikispecies:Page_types|title=Wikispecies:Page types|publisher=Wikispecies|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Policies ==\nWikispecies has disabled local upload and asks users to use images from [[commons:Main Page|Wikimedia Commons]]. Wikispecies does not allow the use of content that does not conform to a free license.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[All Species Foundation]]\n* [[Catalogue of Life]]\n* [[Encyclopedia of Life]]\n* [[Tree of Life Web Project]]\n* [[List of online encyclopedias]]\n* [[The Plant List]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[[species:Main_Page|Wikispecies, The free species directory that anyone can edit]]\n*[[species:Wikispecies:Community_Portal|Species Community Portal]]\n*[[species:Wikispecies:Charter|The Wikispecies Charter]], written by Wales.\n*{{Commons-inline}}\n\n{{Wikimedia Foundation}}\n\n[[Category:Biodiversity databases]]\n[[Category:Biology websites]]\n[[Category:Botanical nomenclature]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2004]]\n[[Category:Multilingual websites]]\n[[Category:Phylogenetics]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy (biology)]]\n[[Category:Wikimedia projects]]\n[[Category:Zoological nomenclature]]\n[[Category:Advertising-free websites]]\n", "name_user": "2605:e000:121b:d61a:41aa:75f1:31e3:b203", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(jay)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikispecies"}
{"title_page": "Dark tourism", "text_new": "[[File:Rwandan Genocide Murambi skulls.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Murambi Technical School]] where many of the murders in the [[Rwandan genocide]] took place is now a genocide museum.]]\n[[File:Catacombs-700px.jpg|thumb|250px|The [[Catacombs of Paris]] have become a popular site for thanatourism, and guided tours are frequently held in small areas of the complex of tunnels and chambers.]]\n'''Dark tourism''' (also '''black tourism''', '''morbid tourism''' or '''grief tourism''') has been defined as [[tourism]] involving travel to places historically associated with [[death]] and [[tragedy (event)|tragedy]].<ref name=\"Lennon\"/> More recently, it was suggested that the concept should also include reasons tourists visit that site, since the site's attributes alone may not make a visitor a \"dark tourist\".<ref name=Rami/> The main attraction to dark locations is their historical value rather than their associations with death and suffering.<ref name=Rami /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gonomad.com/features/0704/dark-tourism.html|work=gonomad.com|title=Shedding Light on Dark Tourism|author= Courtney C. Reed|accessdate=1 March 2014|date=April 2007}}</ref> [[Holocaust tourism]] contains aspects of both dark tourism and [[heritage tourism]].\n\n==Field of study==\nWhile there is a long tradition of people visiting recent and ancient settings of death, such as travel to [[gladiator]] games in the Roman [[colosseum]], attending public executions by [[decapitation]], and visiting the [[catacombs]], this practice has been studied academically only relatively recently.\nTravel writers were the first to describe their tourism to deadly places. [[P. J. O'Rourke]] called his travel to [[Warsaw]], [[Managua]], and [[Belfast]] in 1988 'holidays in hell',<ref>{{cite book|last=O'Rourke|first=P. J.|title=Holidays in Hell|year=1989|publisher=Picador|location=London|isbn=978-0330306836|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/holidaysinhell00orou_0}}</ref> or Chris Rojek talking about 'black-spot' tourism in 1993<ref>{{cite book|last=Rojek|first=Chris|title=Ways of Escape: Modern Transformations in Leisure and Travel|year=1993|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|location=London|isbn=978-0333475782|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Ways_of_escape.html?id=Ex1HAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=1 March 2014|quote=(P 142)The leisure forms constructed around black spots certainly give signs of repetition-compulsion and seeking the duplication of experience. (p170) The gravity and solemnity of Black Spots have been reduced by moves to make them more colorful and more spectacular than other sights on the tourist trail. For example, in 1987 the government of Thailand unveiled plans to restore the famous Death Railway \u2026}}</ref> or the 'milking the macabre'.<ref name=Dann>{{cite book|title=Global Tourism: The Next Decade|year=1994|publisher=Butterworth Heinemann|location=Oxford|pages=55\u201367|last=Dann|first= G|chapter=Tourism the nostalgia industry of the future|editor=W. Theobald}}</ref>\n\nAcademic attention to the subject originated in [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]: The term 'dark tourism' was coined in 1996 by Lennon and Foley, two faculty members of the Department of Hospitality, Tourism & Leisure Management at [[Glasgow Caledonian University]],<ref name=\"Lennon\">{{cite journal|last=Foley|first=Malcolm|author2=J. John Lennon|title=JFK and dark tourism: A fascination with assassination|journal=International Journal of Heritage Studies|year=1996|volume=2|issue=4|pages=198\u2013211| doi=10.1080/13527259608722175}}</ref> and the term 'thanatourism' was first mentioned by A. V. Seaton in 1996, then Professor of Tourism Marketing at the [[University of Strathclyde]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Seaton|first=AV|title=Guided by the dark: from thanatopsis to thanatourism|journal=Int Journal of Heritage Studies|year=1996|volume=2|issue=4|pages=234\u2013244|doi=10.1080/13527259608722178|url=https://books.google.com/?id=OeXWAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA1&dq=thanatourism#v=onepage&q=thanatourism&f=false|accessdate=1 March 2014|isbn=9781136394966}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2014, there have been many studies on definitions, labels, and subcategorizations, such as [[Holocaust tourism]] and slavery-heritage tourism, and the term continues to be molded outside academia by authors of travel literature.<ref>{{cite book|title=Writings On The Dark Side Of Travel|date=March 15, 2012|publisher=Berghahn Books|isbn=978-0857453419| editor=Jonathan Skinner}}</ref> There is very little [[empirical research]] on the perspective of the dark tourist.<ref name=Rami>{{cite journal|author1=Rami Khalil Isaac |author2=Erdin\u00e7 \u00c7akmak |title=Understanding visitor's motivation at sites of death and disaster: the case of former transit camp Westerbork, the Netherlands|journal=Current Issues in Tourism|volume=17 |issue=2 |year=2013|pages=1\u201316|doi=10.1080/13683500.2013.776021}}</ref>\nDark tourism has been formally studied from three main perspectives by a variety of different disciplines:\n\n===Hospitality and tourism===\nScholars in this interdisciplinary field have examined many different aspects. Lennon and Foley expanded their original idea <ref name=\"Lennon\"/> in their first book, deploring that \"tact and taste do not prevail over economic considerations\u201d and that the \"blame for transgressions cannot lie solely on the shoulders of the proprietors, but also upon those of the tourists, for without their demand there would be no need to supply.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Dark tourism: The attraction of death and disasters|year=2000|publisher=Thomson Learning|location=London|author=Lennon, J.|author2=Foley, M.}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n\n===The exploitation of the deceased===\nWhether a tourist attraction is educational or exploitative is defined by both its operators and its visitors.<ref name=\"jeju\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jejuweekly.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=776|title=Exploitation or healthy interest? An analysis of dark tourism.|author= Darryl Coote|date= 2010-06-12|publisher=Jeju Weekly|accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref> Tourism operators motivated by greed can \"milk the macabre\"<ref name=Dann /> or reexamine tragedies for a learning experience. Tourists consuming dark tourism products may desecrate a place and case studies are needed to probe who gains and loses.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oNSFAgAAQBAJ&dq|title=Contemporary issues in tourist development|editor1=Richard W. Butler |editor2=Douglas G. |page =122|year=1999|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1134623600}}</ref>\n\nThanatourism and [[slum tourism]] have been described as re-interpreting the pastime according to the needs of financial elite.<ref>Tzanelli R (2016) Thana Tourism and the Cinematic Representation of Risk. Abingdon, Routledge.</ref>\n\n===Misinformation===\n[[Chris Hedges]] described the \"[[Alcatraz]] narrative as presented by the [[National Park Service]]\" as \"[[whitewashing (censorship)|whitewashing]]\", because it \"...ignores the savagery and injustice of America's system of mass incarceration\". By omitting challenging details, the park service furthers a \"[[Disneyfication]]\", per Hedges.<ref name=hedges>{{cite news|author1=Chris Hedges|title=Alcatraz: A Prison as Disneyland|url=http://www.truthdig.com/report/item/alcatraz_a_prison_as_disneyworld_20141130|work=Truthdig.com|publisher=Zuade Kaufman|accessdate=5 December 2014|date=30 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Example destinations==\nDestinations of dark tourism include: castles and battlefields such as [[Battle of Culloden#Culloden battlefield today|Culloden]] in Scotland and [[Bran Castle]] and [[Poienari Castle]] in Romania; former [[prison]]s such as [[Beaumaris Prison]] in [[Anglesey]], Wales and the [[Jack the Ripper]] exhibition in the [[London Dungeon]]; sites of [[natural disaster]]s or [[Anthropogenic hazard|man made disaster]]s, such as [[Hiroshima Peace Memorial Park]] in Japan,<ref>{{cite web|title=Hiroshima Peace Memorial Museum website|url=http://www.pcf.city.hiroshima.jp/index_e2.html|work=[[Hiroshima Peace Memorial Museum]]|accessdate=1 March 2014|year=2011}}</ref> [[Chernobyl]] in Ukraine<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chernobylpripyat.com/ |publisher=chernobylpripyat.com |title=Chernobylzone |accessdate=February 25, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225173644/http://www.chernobylpripyat.com/ |archivedate=February 25, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukrainianweb.com/chernobyl_ukraine.htm|title=Chernobyl Tours|publisher= Ukrainianweb.com|accessdate=February 28, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chernobyl-tour.com/english|publisher=Chernobyl-TOUR|title=Chernobyl tour, official provider of Chernobyl exclusion zone|accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref> and the commercial activity at [[World Trade Center site|Ground Zero]] in New York one year after [[September 11, 2001]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/06/28/1023864657451.html|work=2002 The Age Company Ltd|author=Jayson Blair|date=June 29, 2002|title=Tragedy turns to tourism at Ground Zero|accessdate=March 1, 2014}}</ref> It also includes sites of human atrocities and [[genocide]], such as the [[Auschwitz concentration camp]] in Poland,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.auschwitz.org/m/|title=Memorial Museum Auschwitz Birkenau|publisher=[[Pa\u0144stwowe Muzeum Auschwitz-Birkenau]] w O\u015bwi\u0119cimiu|accessdate=February 28, 2014}}</ref> the [[Nanjing Massacre Memorial Hall]] in China, the [[Tuol Sleng Genocide Museum]] in Cambodia; the sites of the [[Jeju Uprising]] in South Korea<ref name=\"jeju\" /> and the Spirit Lake Internment Camp Centre near [[Tr\u00e9cesson, Quebec|La Ferme, Quebec]] as an example of [[Ukrainian Canadian internment|Canada's internment operations]] of 1914\u20131920.<ref>{{cite web|title=Launch of Quebec Internment Spirit Lake Interpretive Centre|url=http://www.internmentcanada.ca/PDF/articles/Spirit_Lake.pdf.|work=press release|publisher=[[Canadian First World War Internment Recognition Fund]]|accessdate=February 28, 2014|date=July 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn Bali \"death and funeral rites have become [[commodification|commodified]] for tourism ..., where enterprising businesses begin arranging tourist vans and sell tickets as soon as they hear someone is dying.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=McLaren|first=Deborah|title=Rethinking Tourism and Ecotravel|date=June 2003|publisher=Kumarian Press|isbn=978-1565491694|page=[https://archive.org/details/rethinkingtouris02edmcla/page/48 48]|url=https://archive.org/details/rethinkingtouris02edmcla|url-access=registration|edition=2|accessdate=1 March 2014|quote=One of the most disturbing phenomena in Bali is the commercialization of cremation ceremonies.}}</ref> In the US, visitors can tour the [[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum|Holocaust Memorial Museum]] in Washington D.C. \"with an identity card which matches their age and gender with that of a name and photo of a real holocaust victim. Against a backdrop of video interpretation portraying killing squads in action, the pseudo holocaust victim enters a personal ID into monitors as they wander around the attraction to discover how their real-life counterpart is faring.\"<ref name=Stone>{{cite journal|last=Stone|first=P|title=Dark Tourism Consumption \u2013 A call for research|journal=E-Review of Tourism Research|year=2005|volume=2|issue=5|pages=109\u2013117|quote=contemporary society with its ...late capitalism broad defining features include an increased commercial ethic and commodification; a de-differentiation of time and space through global technological communication; and an introduction of anxiety and doubt over the project of modernity.}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Disaster tourism]]\n* [[Slum tourism]]\n* [[War tourism]]\n* [[Dark Tourist (television series)]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2013/oct/31/dark-tourism-murder-sites-disaster-zones \"What is dark tourism?\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'' special feature\n*[http://www.life.com/image/first/in-gallery/49261/chernobyl-unlikely-tourist-spot#index/0 Chernobyl: Unlikely Tourist Spot] - slideshow by ''[[Life magazine]]''\n\n{{Death}}\n{{Tourism}}\n\n[[Category:Cultural tourism]]\n[[Category:Grief]]\n[[Category:Cultural aspects of death]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Rwandan Genocide Murambi skulls.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Murambi Technical School]] where many of the murders in the [[Rwandan genocide]] took place is now a genocide museum.]]\n[[File:Catacombs-700px.jpg|thumb|250px|The [[Catacombs of Paris]] have become a popular site for thanatourism, and guided tours are frequently held in small areas of the complex of tunnels and chambers.]]\n'''Dark tourism''' (also '''black tourism ''', '''morbid tourism ''' or '''grief tourism''') has been defined as [[tourism]] involving travel to places historically associated with [[death]] and [[tragedy (event)|tragedy]].<ref name=\"Lennon\"/> More recently, it was suggested that the concept should also include reasons tourists visit that site, since the site's attributes alone may not make a visitor a \"dark tourist\".<ref name=Rami/> The main attraction to dark locations is their historical value rather than their associations with death and suffering.<ref name=Rami /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gonomad.com/features/0704/dark-tourism.html|work=gonomad.com|title=Shedding Light on Dark Tourism|author= Courtney C. Reed|accessdate=1 March 2014|date=April 2007}}</ref> [[Holocaust tourism]] contains aspects of both dark tourism and [[heritage tourism]].\n\n==Field of study==\nWhile there is a long tradition of people visiting recent and ancient settings of death, such as travel to [[gladiator]] games in the Roman [[colosseum]], attending public executions by [[decapitation]], and visiting the [[catacombs]], this practice has been studied academically only relatively recently.\nTravel writers were the first to describe their tourism to deadly places. [[P. J. O'Rourke]] called his travel to [[Warsaw]], [[Managua]], and [[Belfast]] in 1988 'holidays in hell',<ref>{{cite book|last=O'Rourke|first=P. J.|title=Holidays in Hell|year=1989|publisher=Picador|location=London|isbn=978-0330306836|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/holidaysinhell00orou_0}}</ref> or Chris Rojek talking about 'black-spot' tourism in 1993<ref>{{cite book|last=Rojek|first=Chris|title=Ways of Escape: Modern Transformations in Leisure and Travel|year=1993|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|location=London|isbn=978-0333475782|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Ways_of_escape.html?id=Ex1HAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=1 March 2014|quote=(P 142)The leisure forms constructed around black spots certainly give signs of repetition-compulsion and seeking the duplication of experience. (p170) The gravity and solemnity of Black Spots have been reduced by moves to make them more colorful and more spectacular than other sights on the tourist trail. For example, in 1987 the government of Thailand unveiled plans to restore the famous Death Railway \u2026}}</ref> or the 'milking the macabre'.<ref name=Dann>{{cite book|title=Global Tourism: The Next Decade|year=1994|publisher=Butterworth Heinemann|location=Oxford|pages=55\u201367|last=Dann|first= G|chapter=Tourism the nostalgia industry of the future|editor=W. Theobald}}</ref>\n\nAcademic attention to the subject originated in [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]: The term 'dark tourism' was coined in 1996 by Lennon and Foley, two faculty members of the Department of Hospitality, Tourism & Leisure Management at [[Glasgow Caledonian University]],<ref name=\"Lennon\">{{cite journal|last=Foley|first=Malcolm|author2=J. John Lennon|title=JFK and dark tourism: A fascination with assassination|journal=International Journal of Heritage Studies|year=1996|volume=2|issue=4|pages=198\u2013211| doi=10.1080/13527259608722175}}</ref> and the term 'thanatourism' was first mentioned by A. V. Seaton in 1996, then Professor of Tourism Marketing at the [[University of Strathclyde]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Seaton|first=AV|title=Guided by the dark: from thanatopsis to thanatourism|journal=Int Journal of Heritage Studies|year=1996|volume=2|issue=4|pages=234\u2013244|doi=10.1080/13527259608722178|url=https://books.google.com/?id=OeXWAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA1&dq=thanatourism#v=onepage&q=thanatourism&f=false|accessdate=1 March 2014|isbn=9781136394966}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2014, there have been many studies on definitions, labels, and subcategorizations, such as  [[Holocaust tourism]] and slavery-heritage tourism, and the term continues to be molded outside academia by authors of travel literature.<ref>{{cite book|title=Writings On The Dark Side Of Travel|date=March 15, 2012|publisher=Berghahn Books|isbn=978-0857453419| editor=Jonathan Skinner}}</ref> There is very little [[empirical research]] on the perspective of the dark tourist.<ref name=Rami>{{cite journal|author1=Rami Khalil Isaac |author2=Erdin\u00e7 \u00c7akmak |title=Understanding visitor's motivation at sites of death and disaster: the case of former transit camp Westerbork, the Netherlands|journal=Current Issues in Tourism|volume=17 |issue=2 |year=2013|pages=1\u201316|doi=10.1080/13683500.2013.776021}}</ref> \nDark tourism has been formally studied from three main perspectives by a variety of different disciplines:\n\n===Hospitality and tourism===\nScholars in this interdisciplinary field have examined many different aspects. Lennon and Foley expanded their original idea <ref name=\"Lennon\"/> in their first book, deploring that \"tact and taste do not prevail over economic considerations\u201d and that the \"blame for transgressions cannot lie solely on the shoulders of the proprietors, but also upon those of the tourists, for without their demand there would be no need to supply.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Dark tourism: The attraction of death and disasters|year=2000|publisher=Thomson Learning|location=London|author=Lennon, J.|author2=Foley, M.}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n\n===The exploitation of the deceased===\nWhether a tourist attraction is educational or exploitative is defined by both its operators and its visitors.<ref name=\"jeju\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jejuweekly.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=776|title=Exploitation or healthy interest? An analysis of dark tourism.|author= Darryl Coote|date= 2010-06-12|publisher=Jeju Weekly|accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref> Tourism operators motivated by greed can \"milk the macabre\"<ref name=Dann /> or reexamine tragedies for a learning experience. Tourists consuming dark tourism products may desecrate a place and case studies are needed to probe who gains and loses.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oNSFAgAAQBAJ&dq|title=Contemporary issues in tourist development|editor1=Richard W. Butler |editor2=Douglas G. |page =122|year=1999|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1134623600}}</ref>\n\nThanatourism and [[slum tourism]] have been described as re-interpreting the pastime according to the needs of financial elite.<ref>Tzanelli R (2016) Thana Tourism and the Cinematic Representation of Risk. Abingdon, Routledge.</ref>\n\n===Misinformation===\n[[Chris Hedges]] described the \"[[Alcatraz]] narrative as presented by the [[National Park Service]]\" as \"[[whitewashing (censorship)|whitewashing]]\", because it \"...ignores the savagery and injustice of America's system of mass incarceration\". By omitting challenging details, the park service furthers a \"[[Disneyfication]]\", per Hedges.<ref name=hedges>{{cite news|author1=Chris Hedges|title=Alcatraz: A Prison as Disneyland|url=http://www.truthdig.com/report/item/alcatraz_a_prison_as_disneyworld_20141130|work=Truthdig.com|publisher=Zuade Kaufman|accessdate=5 December 2014|date=30 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Example destinations==\nDestinations of dark tourism include: castles and battlefields such as [[Battle of Culloden#Culloden battlefield today|Culloden]] in Scotland and [[Bran Castle]] and [[Poienari Castle]] in Romania; former [[prison]]s such as [[Beaumaris Prison]] in [[Anglesey]], Wales and the [[Jack the Ripper]] exhibition in the [[London Dungeon]]; sites of [[natural disaster]]s or [[Anthropogenic hazard|man made disaster]]s, such as [[Hiroshima Peace Memorial Park]] in Japan,<ref>{{cite web|title=Hiroshima Peace Memorial Museum website|url=http://www.pcf.city.hiroshima.jp/index_e2.html|work=[[Hiroshima Peace Memorial Museum]]|accessdate=1 March 2014|year=2011}}</ref> [[Chernobyl]] in Ukraine<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chernobylpripyat.com/ |publisher=chernobylpripyat.com |title=Chernobylzone |accessdate=February 25, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225173644/http://www.chernobylpripyat.com/ |archivedate=February 25, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukrainianweb.com/chernobyl_ukraine.htm|title=Chernobyl Tours|publisher= Ukrainianweb.com|accessdate=February 28, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chernobyl-tour.com/english|publisher=Chernobyl-TOUR|title=Chernobyl tour, official provider of Chernobyl exclusion zone|accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref> and the commercial activity at [[World Trade Center site|Ground Zero]] in New York one year after [[September 11, 2001]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/06/28/1023864657451.html|work=2002 The Age Company Ltd|author=Jayson Blair|date=June 29, 2002|title=Tragedy turns to tourism at Ground Zero|accessdate=March 1, 2014}}</ref> It also includes sites of human atrocities and [[genocide]], such as the [[Auschwitz concentration camp]] in Poland,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.auschwitz.org/m/|title=Memorial Museum Auschwitz Birkenau|publisher=[[Pa\u0144stwowe Muzeum Auschwitz-Birkenau]] w O\u015bwi\u0119cimiu|accessdate=February 28, 2014}}</ref> the [[Nanjing Massacre Memorial Hall]] in China, the [[Tuol Sleng Genocide Museum]] in Cambodia; the sites of the [[Jeju Uprising]] in South Korea<ref name=\"jeju\" /> and the Spirit Lake Internment Camp Centre near [[Tr\u00e9cesson, Quebec|La Ferme, Quebec]] as an example of [[Ukrainian Canadian internment|Canada's internment operations]] of 1914\u20131920.<ref>{{cite web|title=Launch of Quebec Internment Spirit Lake Interpretive Centre|url=http://www.internmentcanada.ca/PDF/articles/Spirit_Lake.pdf.|work=press release|publisher=[[Canadian First World War Internment Recognition Fund]]|accessdate=February 28, 2014|date=July 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn Bali \"death and funeral rites have become [[commodification|commodified]] for tourism ..., where enterprising businesses begin arranging tourist vans and sell tickets as soon as they hear someone is dying.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=McLaren|first=Deborah|title=Rethinking Tourism and Ecotravel|date=June 2003|publisher=Kumarian Press|isbn=978-1565491694|page=[https://archive.org/details/rethinkingtouris02edmcla/page/48 48]|url=https://archive.org/details/rethinkingtouris02edmcla|url-access=registration|edition=2|accessdate=1 March 2014|quote=One of the most disturbing phenomena in Bali is the commercialization of cremation ceremonies.}}</ref> In the US, visitors can tour the [[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum|Holocaust Memorial Museum]] in Washington D.C. \"with an identity card which matches their age and gender with that of a name and photo of a real holocaust victim. Against a backdrop of video interpretation portraying killing squads in action, the pseudo holocaust victim enters a personal ID into monitors as they wander around the attraction to discover how their real-life counterpart is faring.\"<ref name=Stone>{{cite journal|last=Stone|first=P|title=Dark Tourism Consumption \u2013 A call for research|journal=E-Review of Tourism Research|year=2005|volume=2|issue=5|pages=109\u2013117|quote=contemporary society with its ...late capitalism broad defining features include an increased commercial ethic and commodification; a de-differentiation of time and space through global technological communication; and an introduction of anxiety and doubt over the project of modernity.}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Disaster tourism]]\n* [[Slum tourism]]\n* [[War tourism]]\n* [[Dark Tourist (television series)]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2013/oct/31/dark-tourism-murder-sites-disaster-zones \"What is dark tourism?\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'' special feature\n*[http://www.life.com/image/first/in-gallery/49261/chernobyl-unlikely-tourist-spot#index/0 Chernobyl: Unlikely Tourist Spot] - slideshow by ''[[Life magazine]]''\n\n{{Death}}\n{{Tourism}}\n\n[[Category:Cultural tourism]]\n[[Category:Grief]]\n[[Category:Cultural aspects of death]]\n", "name_user": "Orcaguy", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed extraneous spaces", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dark_tourism"}
{"title_page": "Back at the Barnyard", "text_new": "{{short description|Computer-animated television series}}\n{{about|the series|the film|Barnyard (film)}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=August 2010}}\n{{overly detailed|date=January 2013}}\n{{in-universe|date=April 2014}}\n}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = Back at the Barnyard\n| image = Back at the Barnyard title.png\n| genre = [[Animated sitcom]]\n| creator = [[Steve Oedekerk]]\n| director = Todd Grimes<br />T.J. Sullivan<br />Mike Gasaway<br />[[Spike Brandt]]<br />[[Tony Cervone]]<br />Tom Grevera<br />Bert Ring<br />Aaron Hammersley<br />Jim Schumann<br />Fred Gonzales<br />Nick Simotas\n| voices = [[Chris Hardwick]]<br />[[Jeffrey Garcia|Jeff Garcia]]<br />[[Leigh-Allyn Baker]]<br />[[Tino Insana]]<br />[[Cam Clarke]]<br />[[Rob Paulsen]]<br />[[Dom Irrera]]<br />[[Wanda Sykes]]<br />[[Fred Tatasciore]]<br />[[Maria Bamford]]<br />[[Steve Oedekerk]]\n| theme_music_composer = [[Michael Fitzpatrick (musician)|Michael Fitzpatrick]]<br />[[Mickey Petralia]]\n| opentheme = \"''Back at the Barnyard'' Theme Song\" performed by Michael Fitzpatrick & Mickey Petralia\n| composer = [[Guy Moon]]\n| country = United States\n| num_seasons = 3\n| num_episodes = 58\n| list_episodes = List of Back at the Barnyard episodes\n| executive_producer = Steve Oedekerk<br />Jed Spingarn\n| producer = Maragret M. Dean<br /><small>(Season 1)</small><br />Paul Marshal\n| runtime = 11 minutes<br>22 minutes (specials)<br>48 minutes (TV movie)\n| company = [[Steve Oedekerk|O Entertainment]]<br>(2007)<br>(season 1)<br>[[Steve Oedekerk|Omation Animation Studio]]<br>(2008\u201311)<br>(seasons 1\u20132)<br>[[Nickelodeon Animation Studio]]\n| distributor = [[Viacom Media Networks|ViacomCBS Domestic Media Networks]]\n| network = [[Nickelodeon]] <small>(2007\u201310)</small><br>[[Nicktoons (American TV channel)|Nicktoons]] <small>(2011)</small>\n | picture_format = [[480i]] ([[4:3]] [[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])\n| audio_format = [[Dolby Digital|Dolby Digital 5.1]] (2007\u201310)<br>[[Dolby Surround 7.1]] (2010\u201311)\n| first_aired = {{start date|2007|9|29}}\n| last_aired =  {{end date|2011|11|12}}\n| preceded_by = ''[[Barnyard (film)|Barnyard]]'' (2006)\n| followed_by = \n| website = \n| image_size =\n}}\n'''''Back at the Barnyard''''' (also known as '''''Barnyard: The Series''''') is a [[Nickelodeon]] [[computer-animated]] television series that is a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] from the 2006 film, ''[[Barnyard (film)|Barnyard]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |pages=55-56}}</ref> The series aired from September 29, 2007 to September 18, 2010 on Nickelodeon. The show was a co-production between [[Steve Oedekerk#Animation|Omation Animation Studio]] and  [[Nickelodeon Animation Studio]]. The remaining episodes aired from September 12 to November 12, 2011 on Nicktoons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/back-at-the-barnyard/episodes/289619|title=Back at the Barnyard {{!}} TV Guide|website=TVGuide.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-14}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nThe plot generally revolves around Otis, a [[cow]], and his barnyard friends. Otis wants to horse around, but has to be responsible and protect the inhabitants of the Barnyard. He and his friends Pip the [[mouse]], Abby the cow (who replaced Daisy in the film), Pig the pig, Freddy the [[ferret]], Peck the [[rooster]], Duke the sheepdog, and Bessy the cow have many crazy adventures, while at the same time help Otis protect the farm. The setting is unknown but it is heavily implied to be in the fictional [[Arizona]] town of Oedeville. Otis and his friends have to overtake many obstacles like preventing Mrs. Beady from proving that animals know how to  talk and distracting the farmer, so that they can throw a party. In many episodes, Otis gets himself in a sticky situation where his friends have to come to the rescue, resulting in him learning a lesson. Sometimes, the animals dress up like people when out in public, which nobody notices except Mrs. Beady.\n\n==Characters==\n{{main|List of Back at the Barnyard characters}}\n\n*Otis (voiced by [[Chris Hardwick]]) \n*Pip (voiced by [[Jeff Garcia (voice actor)|Jeff Garcia]])\n*Abby (voiced by [[Leigh-Allyn Baker]])\n*Pig (voiced by [[Tino Insana]])\n*Freddy (voiced by [[Cam Clarke]])\n*Peck (voiced by [[Rob Paulsen]])\n*Duke (voiced by [[Dom Irrera]])\n*Bessy (voiced by [[Wanda Sykes]])\n*Noreen \"Nora\" Beady (voiced by [[Maria Bamford]])\n*Farmer Buyer (voiced by [[Fred Tatasciore]])\n*Eugene \"Snotty Boy\" Beady (voiced by [[Steve Oedekerk]])\n*Noreen \u201cNora\u201d Beady\u2019s husband (voiced by [[Steve Oedekerk]])\n\n== Episodes ==\n{{main|List of Back at the Barnyard episodes}}\n{{:List of Back at the Barnyard episodes}}\n\n== Video game ==\n{{Infobox video game\n|title= Back at the Barnyard:<br>Slop Bucket Games\n<!-- Commented out: | image= Back at the Barnyard Slop Bucket Games cover.jpg -->\n|caption = North American cover art\n|developer= [[Firemonkeys Studios|Firemint]]\n|publisher= [[THQ|Play THQ]]\n|released = {{vgrelease|NA|October 20, 2008|AUS|October 23, 2008|EU|October 24, 2008}}\n|genre = [[Action game]]\n|modes =\n|platforms = [[Nintendo DS]]\n}}\n'''''Back at the Barnyard: Slop Bucket Games''''' (released PAL regions under the name '''''Back at the Barnyard: Cowlympics''''') is an [[action video game]] released by [[THQ]] in 2008 for the [[Nintendo DS]]. It received generally negative reviews from critics, receiving a 43.86% from [[GameRankings]].<ref name = \"Gamerankings\">[http://www.gamerankings.com/ds/946171-back-at-the-barnyard-slop-bucket-games/index.html Back at the Barnyard: Slop Bucket Games for DS - GameRankings]</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{portal|Nickelodeon|Animation|Comedy}}\n* 