im Schumann<br />Fred Gonzales<br />Nick Simotas\n| voices = [[Chris Hardwick]]<br />[[Jeffrey Garcia|Jeff Garcia]]<br />[[Leigh-Allyn Baker]]<br />[[Tino Insana]]<br />[[Cam Clarke]]<br />[[Rob Paulsen]]<br />[[Dom Irrera]]<br />[[Wanda Sykes]]<br />[[Fred Tatasciore]]<br />[[Maria Bamford]]<br />[[Steve Oedekerk]]\n| theme_music_composer = [[Michael Fitzpatrick (musician)|Michael Fitzpatrick]]<br />[[Mickey Petralia]]\n| opentheme = \"''Back at the Barnyard'' Theme Song\" performed by Michael Fitzpatrick & Mickey Petralia\n| composer = [[Guy Moon]]\n| country = United States\n| num_seasons = 2\n| num_episodes = 52\n| list_episodes = List of Back at the Barnyard episodes\n| executive_producer = Steve Oedekerk<br />Jed Spingarn\n| producer = Maragret M. Dean<br /><small>(Season 1)</small><br />Paul Marshal\n| runtime = 11 minutes<br>22 minutes (specials)<br>48 minutes (TV movie)\n| company = [[Steve Oedekerk|O Entertainment]]<br>(2007)<br>(season 1)<br>[[Steve Oedekerk|Omation Animation Studio]]<br>(2008\u201311)<br>(seasons 1\u20132)<br>[[Nickelodeon Animation Studio]]\n| distributor = [[Viacom Media Networks|ViacomCBS Domestic Media Networks]]\n| network = [[Nickelodeon]] <small>(2007\u201310)</small><br>[[Nicktoons (American TV channel)|Nicktoons]] <small>(2011)</small>\n | picture_format = [[480i]] ([[4:3]] [[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])\n| audio_format = [[Dolby Digital|Dolby Digital 5.1]] (2007\u201310)<br>[[Dolby Surround 7.1]] (2010\u201311)\n| first_aired = {{start date|2007|9|29}}\n| last_aired =  {{end date|2011|11|12}}\n| preceded_by = ''[[Barnyard (film)|Barnyard]]'' (2006)\n| followed_by = \n| website = \n| image_size =\n}}\n'''''Back at the Barnyard''''' (also known as '''''Barnyard: The Series''''') is a [[Nickelodeon]] [[computer-animated]] television series that is a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] from the 2006 film, ''[[Barnyard (film)|Barnyard]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |pages=55-56}}</ref> The series aired from September 29, 2007 to September 18, 2010 on Nickelodeon. The show was a co-production between [[Steve Oedekerk#Animation|Omation Animation Studio]] and  [[Nickelodeon Animation Studio]]. The remaining episodes aired from September 12 to November 12, 2011 on Nicktoons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/back-at-the-barnyard/episodes/289619|title=Back at the Barnyard {{!}} TV Guide|website=TVGuide.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-14}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nThe plot generally revolves around Otis, a [[cow]], and his barnyard friends. Otis wants to horse around, but has to be responsible and protect the inhabitants of the Barnyard. He and his friends Pip the [[mouse]], Abby the cow (who replaced Daisy in the film), Pig the pig, Freddy the [[ferret]], Peck the [[rooster]], Duke the sheepdog, and Bessy the cow have many crazy adventures, while at the same time help Otis protect the farm. The setting is unknown but it is heavily implied to be in the fictional [[Arizona]] town of Oedeville. Otis and his friends have to overtake many obstacles like preventing Mrs. Beady from proving that animals know how to  talk and distracting the farmer, so that they can throw a party. In many episodes, Otis gets himself in a sticky situation where his friends have to come to the rescue, resulting in him learning a lesson. Sometimes, the animals dress up like people when out in public, which nobody notices except Mrs. Beady.\n\n==Characters==\n{{main|List of Back at the Barnyard characters}}\n\n*Otis (voiced by [[Chris Hardwick]]) \n*Pip (voiced by [[Jeff Garcia (voice actor)|Jeff Garcia]])\n*Abby (voiced by [[Leigh-Allyn Baker]])\n*Pig (voiced by [[Tino Insana]])\n*Freddy (voiced by [[Cam Clarke]])\n*Peck (voiced by [[Rob Paulsen]])\n*Duke (voiced by [[Dom Irrera]])\n*Bessy (voiced by [[Wanda Sykes]])\n*Noreen \"Nora\" Beady (voiced by [[Maria Bamford]])\n*Farmer Buyer (voiced by [[Fred Tatasciore]])\n*Eugene \"Snotty Boy\" Beady (voiced by [[Steve Oedekerk]])\n*Noreen \u201cNora\u201d Beady\u2019s husband (voiced by [[Steve Oedekerk]])\n\n== Episodes ==\n{{main|List of Back at the Barnyard episodes}}\n{{:List of Back at the Barnyard episodes}}\n\n== Video game ==\n{{Infobox video game\n|title= Back at the Barnyard:<br>Slop Bucket Games\n<!-- Commented out: | image= Back at the Barnyard Slop Bucket Games cover.jpg -->\n|caption = North American cover art\n|developer= [[Firemonkeys Studios|Firemint]]\n|publisher= [[THQ|Play THQ]]\n|released = {{vgrelease|NA|October 20, 2008|AUS|October 23, 2008|EU|October 24, 2008}}\n|genre = [[Action game]]\n|modes =\n|platforms = [[Nintendo DS]]\n}}\n'''''Back at the Barnyard: Slop Bucket Games''''' (released PAL regions under the name '''''Back at the Barnyard: Cowlympics''''') is an [[action video game]] released by [[THQ]] in 2008 for the [[Nintendo DS]]. It received generally negative reviews from critics, receiving a 43.86% from [[GameRankings]].<ref name = \"Gamerankings\">[http://www.gamerankings.com/ds/946171-back-at-the-barnyard-slop-bucket-games/index.html Back at the Barnyard: Slop Bucket Games for DS - GameRankings]</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{portal|Nickelodeon|Animation|Comedy}}\n* [http://cabletvt.powerrangermail.net/index.php/topic,3446.html Press Release]\n* [http://www.markbeam.com Mark Beam - Character Design / Associate Producer]\n* {{IMDb title|0857277|Back at the Barnyard}}\n* {{bcdb |Other_Studios/O/Omation_Animation_Studio/Back_At_The_Barnyard/|Back At The Barnyard}}\n* {{tv.com show|back-at-the-barnyard|Back at the Barnyard}}\n\n{{Former Nickelodeon original series}}\n\n[[Category:Nicktoons]]\n[[Category:2000s Nickelodeon shows]]\n[[Category:2010s Nickelodeon shows]]\n[[Category:2000s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American children's television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American children's television series]]\n[[Category:2007 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2011 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:American children's animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:American computer-animated television series]]\n[[Category:Animated television programs based on films]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series about cows]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Steve Oedekerk]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Arizona]]\n[[Category:YTV shows]]\n", "name_user": "31.161.5.122", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Edcvdsvgdz)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Back_at_the_Barnyard"}
{"title_page": "Ign\u00e1c Martinovics", "text_new": "{{Expand Hungarian|Martinovics Ign\u00e1c|date=June 2010}}\n\n[[File:Martinovics Ign\u00e1c J\u00f3zsef Domonkos egykor\u00fa rajz ut\u00e1n.jpg|thumb|Portrait of Ign\u00e1c Martinovics]]\n'''Ign\u00e1c Martinovics''' ({{lang-sh|Ignjat Martinovi\u0107}}, \u0418\u0433\u045a\u0430\u0442 \u041c\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u045b; 20 July 1755 &ndash; 20 May 1795) was a [[Kingdom of Hungary|Hungarian]] scholar, philosopher, writer, secret agent, [[Freemason]] and a leader of the [[Hungary|Hungarian]] [[Jacobin]] movement. He was condemned to death for high treason and beheaded on 20 May 1795, along with count Jakab Sigray, Ferenc Szentmarjay, J\u00f3zsef Hajn\u00f3czy and others.\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life and education===\nHis father, M\u00e1ty\u00e1s Martinovics was one of the nobles of Albanian descent who as a result of the [[Great Turkish War]] left Ottoman Serbia in 1690 under the leadership of [[Arsenije III \u010carnojevi\u0107]] during the [[Great Migrations of the Serbs#First migration|Great Migrations of the Serbs]] and resettled in [[D\u00e9lvid\u00e9k]], [[Kingdom of Hungary (1526\u20131867)|Hungary]].<ref name=\"Lendvai184\"/><ref name=\"Fine539\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kcns.org.rs/agora/koncepcije-o-srpskoj-vojvodini-iliriku-dunavskoj-konfederaciji-istocnoj-svajcarskoj/|title=Koncepcije o Srpskoj Vojvodini, Iliriku, Dunavskoj konfederaciji, Isto\u010dnoj \u0160vajcarskoj...|date=2018-09-07|website=Kulturni centar Novog Sada|language=sr-RS|access-date=2019-01-23}}</ref><ref name=\"fraknoi\">Vilmos Frakn\u00f3i, Martinovics \u00e9lete, p. 11, Budapest, 1921, Az Athenaeum Irodalmi \u00c9s Nyomdai R.-T. Kiad\u00e1sa, [http://mek.oszk.hu/09100/09194/09194.pdf]</ref><ref>Dr. Zsigmond V\u00e1rady, Martinovics Ign\u00e1c, p. 19, 1909 Deutsch Zsigmond \u00e9s t\u00e1rsa k\u00f6nyvkeresked\u00e9se, [http://mtdaportal.extra.hu/books/varady_zsigmond_martinovics_ignac.pdf]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kcns.org.rs/agora/koncepcije-o-srpskoj-vojvodini-iliriku-dunavskoj-konfederaciji-istocnoj-svajcarskoj/|title=\u041a\u043e\u043d\u0446\u0435\u043f\u0446\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u043e \u0421\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0458 \u0412\u043e\u0458\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0438, \u0418\u043b\u0438\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0443, \u0414\u0443\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0458 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0444\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0458\u0438, \u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u043e\u0458 \u0428\u0432\u0430\u0458\u0446\u0430\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0458...|date=2018-09-07|website=\u041a\u0443\u043b\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043d\u0438 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430\u0440 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0433 \u0421\u0430\u0434\u0430|language=sr-RS|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>  During his lifetime, Ign\u00e1c Martinovics stated that his father was either a Serb tavern keeper or an Albanian noble in military service.<ref name=\"Lendvai184\">{{cite book|last=Lendvai|first=Paul|title=The Hungarians: A thousand years of victory in defeat|year=2004|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=9780691119694|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=LWOYDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA184&dq=Ign%C3%A1c+Martinovics+albanian&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwih4sH0xOLnAhXY73MBHZAUDIsQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Ign%C3%A1c%20Martinovics%20albanian&f=false|pages=184|ref=harv}}</ref> M\u00e1ty\u00e1s Martinovics served in the Austrian army<ref name=\"Fine539\"/>, he converted from Eastern Orthodoxy to Carholicism and his family moved to [[Pest, Hungary|Pest]] in the second half of the 17th century.<ref name=\"Fine539\"/> There he married M\u00e1ria Poppini,<ref name=\"fraknoi\"/> a German<ref name=\"Lendvai184\"/> commoner from [[Buda]], they had five sons and two daughters.\nIgn\u00e1c Martinovics was born in [[Pest, Hungary|Pest]] and educated by Franciscans<ref name=\"Fine539\">{{cite book|last=Fine|first=John VA|title=When Ethnicity Did Not Matter in the Balkans: A Study of Identity in Pre-Nationalist Croatia, Dalmatia, and Slavonia in the Medieval and Early-Modern Periods|year=2006|publisher=University of Michigan Press|isbn=9780472025602|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=wEF5oN5erE0C&pg=PA539&dq=Ignjat+Martinovi%C4%87&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjkpI6rxOLnAhWzguYKHag9BqMQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Ignjat%20Martinovi%C4%87&f=false|pages=539|ref=harv}}</ref> He finished his first classes in a [[Piarist]] school and chose to enter the [[Franciscan]] order. Martinovics took theological studies in the university of Buda from 1775-1779. \n\n===Political activity and execution===\n[[File:The execution of Martinovics and his comrades on the V\u00e9rmez\u0151 1795.jpg|thumb|left|The execution of Martinovics and his comrades on the V\u00e9rmez\u0151 1795]]\n[[File:Martinovics Ign\u00e1c.jpg|thumb|Martinovics Ign\u00e1c]]\nFrom 1783 he was a teacher in [[natural sciences]] at the [[University of Lemberg]]. During his academic career in Lemberg he joined to the Austrian secret agency, where his talents were recognized. During that time, he had to travel a lot, he accomplished many missions at home and abroad.\n\nAfter the death of the Holy Roman Emperor, [[Joseph II, Holy Roman Emperor|Joseph II]], in February 1790, enlightened reforms in Hungary ceased, which outraged many reform-oriented [[francophone]] intellectuals who were followers of new radical ideas based on French philosophy and enlightenment.\n\nMartinovics career in the secret agency became successful, he was applied as a personal secret agent by [[Holy Roman Emperor Leopold II]] until 1792. In his ''Oratio pro Leopoldo II'' Martinovics is explicit that only the authority that follows from a [[social contract]] should be recognized; he saw the aristocracy as the enemy of mankind, because they prevented people from becoming educated. In another of his works, ''Catechism of People and Citizens,'' he argued that citizens tend to oppose any repression and that sovereignty resides with the people. As the founder of the [[Kingdom of Hungary|Hungarian]] [[Jacobin|Jacobin Club]]s, he was considered an idealistic forerunner of great thought by some, and an unscrupulous adventurer by others. He became a [[Freemason]]. He was in favour of a federal republic for Hungary, thus he established two republican secret clubs: one for aristocratic members, and one for members with bourgeois background. He was in charge of stirring up a revolt against the nobility among the Hungarian serfs. He established four territorial directorates for the secret societies, their directors were J\u00e1nos Laczkovics, J\u00f3zsef Hajn\u00f3czy, Ferenc Szentmarjay and Jakab Sigray.  The new monarch, [[Emperor Francis II]] dismissed Martinovics and his boss, Ferenc Gotthardi, the former chief of the secret police, for these subversive acts.  He was executed, together with six other prominent Jacobins, on 20 May 1795. More than 42 members of the republican secret society were arrested, including the poet [[J\u00e1nos Bats\u00e1nyi]] and linguist [[Ferenc Kazinczy]].<ref>Charles W. Ingrao : The Habsburg Monarchy, 1618\u20131815,  Volume 21 of New Approaches to European History, Publisher: Cambridge University Press, 2000 {{ISBN|9781107268692}}</ref><ref>Jean Berenger, C.A. Simpson: The Habsburg Empire 1700-1918 , Publisher: Routledge, 2014, {{ISBN|9781317895725}}</ref><ref>Tomasz Kamusella: The Politics of Language and Nationalism in Modern Central Europe, Publisher: Palgrave Macmillan, 2009, {{ISBN|9780230550704}}</ref><ref>Paschalis M. Kitromilides: Enlightenment and Revolution, Publisher: Harvard University Press, 2013, {{ISBN|9780674726413}}</ref><ref>Peter McPhee:  A Companion to the French Revolution -PAGE: 391 , Publisher: John Wiley & Sons, 2014, {{ISBN|9781118977521}}</ref>\n\n==Honors==\nThe most important masonic lodge of Budapest belonging to the Hungarian Grand Orient is named after him.<ref>http://szabadkomuvesseg.hu/</ref> Two postage stamp were issued in his honour by Hungary; on 12 June 1919<ref>https://colnect.com/en/stamps/stamp/190131-Ign\u00e1c_Martinovics-Social_Revolutionists-Hungary</ref> and on 15 March 1947<ref> https://colnect.com/en/stamps/stamp/179863-Ign%C3%A1c_Martinovics_1755-1795_philosopher-Hungarian_Freedom_Fighters-Hungary</ref>.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\nSources : 'Paul Lendvai Die Ungarn. ''Ein Jahrtausend Sieger in Niederlagen''. [[C. Bertelsmann Verlag]], M\u00fcnchen 1999.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://books.google.hr/books?id=pSxJdE4MYo4C&pg=PA56&lpg=PA56&dq=ignjat+martinovi%C4%87+croat&source=bl&ots=LkAvISaNjj&sig=MZ713DVxBFYTSoK55zugDEInXAM&hl=hr&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiLoK7tjsjfAhWjlosKHVZQBZwQ6AEwDXoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=ignjat%20martinovi%C4%87%20croat&f=false Martinovics plotted a revolution with some Hungarians and Croats]\n* [https://www.bib.irb.hr/127521 Life and work of Ignjat Martinovi\u0107]\n* [http://library.foi.hr/m3/autor.php?B=1&mg=1&lang=hr&H=metelgrad&A=0000013485 Biography]\n* [https://blagamisterije.com/revolucija-koja-se-nije-dogodila-jakobinska-urota-trebala-je-svrgnuti-habsburgovce-i-osloboditi-narode-monarhije/14689/ Martinovics was ordinated priest in Ilok in 1772]\n* [https://hrcak.srce.hr/196324?lang=en Martinovics in the pitfall of Enlightened Absolutism]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martinovics, Ignac}}\n[[Category:1795 deaths]]\n[[Category:1755 births]]\n[[Category:Burials at Kerepesi Cemetery]]\n[[Category:18th-century Hungarian people]]\n[[Category:Jacobins]]\n[[Category:People from Pest, Hungary]]\n[[Category:Hungarian people of Albanian descent]]\n[[Category:Hungarian people of German descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand Hungarian|Martinovics Ign\u00e1c|date=June 2010}}\n\n[[File:Martinovics Ign\u00e1c J\u00f3zsef Domonkos egykor\u00fa rajz ut\u00e1n.jpg|thumb|Portrait of Ign\u00e1c Martinovics]]\n'''Ign\u00e1c Martinovics''' ({{lang-sh|Ignjat Martinovi\u0107}}, \u0418\u0433\u045a\u0430\u0442 \u041c\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u045b; 20 July 1755 &ndash; 20 May 1795) was a [[Kingdom of Hungary|Hungarian]] scholar, philosopher, writer, secret agent, [[Freemason]] and a leader of the [[Hungary|Hungarian]] [[Jacobin]] movement. He was condemned to death for high treason and beheaded on 20 May 1795, along with count Jakab Sigray, Ferenc Szentmarjay, J\u00f3zsef Hajn\u00f3czy and others.\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life and education===\nHis father, M\u00e1ty\u00e1s Martinovics was one of the nobles of Albanian descent who as a result of the [[Great Turkish War]] left Ottoman Serbia in 1690 under the leadership of [[Arsenije III \u010carnojevi\u0107]] during the [[Great Migrations of the Serbs#First migration|Great Migrations of the Serbs]] and resettled in [[D\u00e9lvid\u00e9k]], [[Kingdom of Hungary (1526\u20131867)|Hungary]].<ref name=\"Lendvai184\"/><ref name=\"Fine539\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kcns.org.rs/agora/koncepcije-o-srpskoj-vojvodini-iliriku-dunavskoj-konfederaciji-istocnoj-svajcarskoj/|title=Koncepcije o Srpskoj Vojvodini, Iliriku, Dunavskoj konfederaciji, Isto\u010dnoj \u0160vajcarskoj...|date=2018-09-07|website=Kulturni centar Novog Sada|language=sr-RS|access-date=2019-01-23}}</ref><ref name=\"fraknoi\">Vilmos Frakn\u00f3i, Martinovics \u00e9lete, p. 11, Budapest, 1921, Az Athenaeum Irodalmi \u00c9s Nyomdai R.-T. Kiad\u00e1sa, [http://mek.oszk.hu/09100/09194/09194.pdf]</ref><ref>Dr. Zsigmond V\u00e1rady, Martinovics Ign\u00e1c, p. 19, 1909 Deutsch Zsigmond \u00e9s t\u00e1rsa k\u00f6nyvkeresked\u00e9se, [http://mtdaportal.extra.hu/books/varady_zsigmond_martinovics_ignac.pdf]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kcns.org.rs/agora/koncepcije-o-srpskoj-vojvodini-iliriku-dunavskoj-konfederaciji-istocnoj-svajcarskoj/|title=\u041a\u043e\u043d\u0446\u0435\u043f\u0446\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u043e \u0421\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0458 \u0412\u043e\u0458\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0438, \u0418\u043b\u0438\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0443, \u0414\u0443\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0458 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0444\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0458\u0438, \u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u043e\u0458 \u0428\u0432\u0430\u0458\u0446\u0430\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0458...|date=2018-09-07|website=\u041a\u0443\u043b\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043d\u0438 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430\u0440 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0433 \u0421\u0430\u0434\u0430|language=sr-RS|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>  During his lifetime, Ign\u00e1c Martinovics stated that his father was either a Serb tavern keeper or an Albanian noble in military service.<ref name=\"Lendvai184\">{{cite book|last=Lendvai|first=Paul|title=The Hungarians: A thousand years of victory in defeat|year=2004|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=9780691119694|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=LWOYDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA184&dq=Ign%C3%A1c+Martinovics+albanian&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwih4sH0xOLnAhXY73MBHZAUDIsQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Ign%C3%A1c%20Martinovics%20albanian&f=false|pages=184|ref=harv}}</ref> M\u00e1ty\u00e1s Martinovics served in the Austrian army<ref name=\"Fine539\"/>, he converted from Eastern Orthodoxy to Carholicism and his family moved to [[Pest, Hungary|Pest]] in the second half of the 17th century.<ref name=\"Fine539\"/> There he married M\u00e1ria Poppini,<ref name=\"fraknoi\"/> a German<ref name=\"Lendvai184\"/> commoner from [[Buda]], they had five sons and two daughters.\nIgn\u00e1c Martinovics was born in [[Pest, Hungary|Pest]] and educated by Franciscans<ref name=\"Fine539\">{{cite book|last=Fine|first=John VA|title=When Ethnicity Did Not Matter in the Balkans: A Study of Identity in Pre-Nationalist Croatia, Dalmatia, and Slavonia in the Medieval and Early-Modern Periods|year=2006|publisher=University of Michigan Press|isbn=9780472025602|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=wEF5oN5erE0C&pg=PA539&dq=Ignjat+Martinovi%C4%87&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjkpI6rxOLnAhWzguYKHag9BqMQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Ignjat%20Martinovi%C4%87&f=false|pages=539|ref=harv}}</ref> He finished his first classes in a [[Piarist]] school and chose to enter the [[Franciscan]] order. Martinovics took theological studies in the university of Buda from 1775-1779. \n\n===Political activity and execution===\n[[File:The execution of Martinovics and his comrades on the V\u00e9rmez\u0151 1795.jpg|thumb|left|The execution of Martinovics and his comrades on the V\u00e9rmez\u0151 1795]]\n[[File:Martinovics Ign\u00e1c.jpg|thumb|Martinovics Ign\u00e1c]]\nFrom 1783 he was a teacher in [[natural sciences]] at the [[University of Lemberg]]. During his academic career in Lemberg he joined to the Austrian secret agency, where his talents were recognized.\n\nAfter the death of the Holy Roman Emperor, [[Joseph II, Holy Roman Emperor|Joseph II]], in February 1790, enlightened reforms in Hungary ceased, which outraged many reform-oriented [[francophone]] intellectuals who were followers of new radical ideas based on French philosophy and enlightenment.\n\nMartinovics career in the secret agency became successful, he was applied as a personal secret agent by [[Holy Roman Emperor Leopold II]] until 1792. During that time, he had to travel a lot, he accomplished many missions at home and abroad. In his ''Oratio pro Leopoldo II'' Martinovics is explicit that only the authority that follows from a [[social contract]] should be recognized; he saw the aristocracy as the enemy of mankind, because they prevented people from becoming educated. In another of his works, ''Catechism of People and Citizens,'' he argued that citizens tend to oppose any repression and that sovereignty resides with the people. As the founder of the [[Kingdom of Hungary|Hungarian]] [[Jacobin|Jacobin Club]]s, he was considered an idealistic forerunner of great thought by some, and an unscrupulous adventurer by others. He became a [[Freemason]]. He was in favour of a federal republic for Hungary, thus he established two republican secret clubs: one for aristocratic members, and one for members with bourgeois background. He was in charge of stirring up a revolt against the nobility among the Hungarian serfs. He established four territorial directorates for the secret societies, their directors were J\u00e1nos Laczkovics, J\u00f3zsef Hajn\u00f3czy, Ferenc Szentmarjay and Jakab Sigray.  The new monarch, [[Emperor Francis II]] dismissed Martinovics and his boss, Ferenc Gotthardi, the former chief of the secret police, for these subversive acts.  He was executed, together with six other prominent Jacobins, on 20 May 1795. More than 42 members of the republican secret society were arrested, including the poet [[J\u00e1nos Bats\u00e1nyi]] and linguist [[Ferenc Kazinczy]].<ref>Charles W. Ingrao : The Habsburg Monarchy, 1618\u20131815,  Volume 21 of New Approaches to European History, Publisher: Cambridge University Press, 2000 {{ISBN|9781107268692}}</ref><ref>Jean Berenger, C.A. Simpson: The Habsburg Empire 1700-1918 , Publisher: Routledge, 2014, {{ISBN|9781317895725}}</ref><ref>Tomasz Kamusella: The Politics of Language and Nationalism in Modern Central Europe, Publisher: Palgrave Macmillan, 2009, {{ISBN|9780230550704}}</ref><ref>Paschalis M. Kitromilides: Enlightenment and Revolution, Publisher: Harvard University Press, 2013, {{ISBN|9780674726413}}</ref><ref>Peter McPhee:  A Companion to the French Revolution -PAGE: 391 , Publisher: John Wiley & Sons, 2014, {{ISBN|9781118977521}}</ref>\n\n==Honors==\nThe most important masonic lodge of Budapest belonging to the Hungarian Grand Orient is named after him.<ref>http://szabadkomuvesseg.hu/</ref> Two postage stamp were issued in his honour by Hungary; on 12 June 1919<ref>https://colnect.com/en/stamps/stamp/190131-Ign\u00e1c_Martinovics-Social_Revolutionists-Hungary</ref> and on 15 March 1947<ref> https://colnect.com/en/stamps/stamp/179863-Ign%C3%A1c_Martinovics_1755-1795_philosopher-Hungarian_Freedom_Fighters-Hungary</ref>.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\nSources : 'Paul Lendvai Die Ungarn. ''Ein Jahrtausend Sieger in Niederlagen''. [[C. Bertelsmann Verlag]], M\u00fcnchen 1999.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://books.google.hr/books?id=pSxJdE4MYo4C&pg=PA56&lpg=PA56&dq=ignjat+martinovi%C4%87+croat&source=bl&ots=LkAvISaNjj&sig=MZ713DVxBFYTSoK55zugDEInXAM&hl=hr&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiLoK7tjsjfAhWjlosKHVZQBZwQ6AEwDXoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=ignjat%20martinovi%C4%87%20croat&f=false Martinovics plotted a revolution with some Hungarians and Croats]\n* [https://www.bib.irb.hr/127521 Life and work of Ignjat Martinovi\u0107]\n* [http://library.foi.hr/m3/autor.php?B=1&mg=1&lang=hr&H=metelgrad&A=0000013485 Biography]\n* [https://blagamisterije.com/revolucija-koja-se-nije-dogodila-jakobinska-urota-trebala-je-svrgnuti-habsburgovce-i-osloboditi-narode-monarhije/14689/ Martinovics was ordinated priest in Ilok in 1772]\n* [https://hrcak.srce.hr/196324?lang=en Martinovics in the pitfall of Enlightened Absolutism]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martinovics, Ignac}}\n[[Category:1795 deaths]]\n[[Category:1755 births]]\n[[Category:Burials at Kerepesi Cemetery]]\n[[Category:18th-century Hungarian people]]\n[[Category:Jacobins]]\n[[Category:People from Pest, Hungary]]\n[[Category:Hungarian people of Albanian descent]]\n[[Category:Hungarian people of German descent]]\n", "name_user": "Liltender", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ign%C3%A1c_Martinovics"}
